year. Completed applications must be submitted by
April 30.</p>
<p><b>ST VINCENT DE PAUL THANKS YOU</b> for helping some
residents of our parish pay rents that escalate faster
than their income. In last week’s bulletin, we reported
that in the past 12 months we helped more than 900
people. That included helping over 500 people with
rent – many at serious risk of eviction. Out of every
dollar you give us, we now spend over 70 cents just on
rent. A few years ago, rents we typically helped with
were seldom above $800 a month. Now we regularly
see rents of $1200 to $1800 monthly, and more people
who used to be called “middle class” are turning to
SVdP for emergency assistance. Plus, we continue to
help low or no income individuals and families who
struggle to pay much lower rents in subsidized
housing. Whether you donate online or in the special
collection the ushers (thank you, ushers!) take for
SVdP, most of your dollars help keep roofs over the heads of hundreds of our 
neighbors every year – thank you! <i>Information</i>,
<a href="mailto:bobclifford53@gmail.com?subject=St. Vincent de Paul">Bob 
Clifford</a>, 206-718-4158.</p>
<p><b>A WEEKLY TIP ON CARING FOR OUR COMMON HOME</b>.
Refresh your memory regarding which items your city
or town allows for curbside recycling. Start adding
items to your bin that you normally haven’t recycled.
Remind your family, friends and coworkers to recycle.</p>
